Let W be the annual cost to water and feed the tree.
W = $3

Let E be the earnings from selling lemons each year.
E = L * P = 7 * $1.5 = $10.5

Let N be the net profit from the tree each year.
N = E - W = $10.5 - $3 = $7.5

Carlos starts earning money when his total accumulated profit is greater than the initial cost.
Let Y be the number of years.
The total accumulated profit after Y years is Y * N.
We want to find the smallest integer Y such that Y * N > C.
Y * $7.5 > $90

To find Y, we divide the initial cost by the net profit per year:
Y > C / N
Y > $90 / $7.5
Y > 12

Since Y must be an integer, the smallest integer Y that satisfies Y > 12 is 13.
So, it will take 13 years before he starts earning money on the lemon tree.

